# Abstract {#abstract}

Abstract goes here.

# 1 Introduction {#1-introduction}

How would you feel about controlling a drone with a wave of your hand or just a thought? With over 1 million drones registered under the Federal Aviation Administration, most require a traditional controller. For those with disabilities, a conventional controller might not be feasible, causing a disparity in access. To address this ableism, a glove or mind controller would allow many people with limitations to be unhindered. A glove controller would increase access to people with limited hand dexterity, and a brain controller would let individuals with severe movement limitations control a drone with accuracy similar to a traditional controller. Current hand-controlled drones either rely on drone-equipped cameras for hand tracking or come with gloves that lack robust control features. Our solution is to create a better quality glove that uses basic hand gestures and movements for a robust set of controls, along with adjustable sensitivity to cater to different ability levels. 

## 1.1 Case Scenarios {#1.1-case-scenarios}

Case 1: The user has minimal hand movement, so the system should increase the sensitivity of the movements, enabling the user to control the drone even with small gestures.

Case 2: The user has minimal motor functions but can move the entire arm, so the system should decrease the sensitivity of movements, enabling the user to move the drone with broader movements.

Case 3: The user experiences hand tremors, so the sensor data must be smoothed or filtered to ignore tremors and only register deliberate movements.

## 1.2 Goals and Constraints {#1.2-goals-and-constraints}

Goals:

* Research and Acquire Sensors: Investigate and purchase the necessary sensors to capture hand and arm movements  
* Test and Understand Sensors: Experiment with the sensors to understand their outputs and how they will interact with the system  
* Integrate with Microchip: Connect the sensors to the Raspberry Pi to test and process sensor data  
* Send Commands to Drone: Develop a system where the user can control a drone via sensor inputs. Initially, control commands may be manually input before integrating with the sensors.  
* User-friendly System: Build a system that accommodates a variety of users with different dexterity levels  
* Integrate Brain-Reader Technology: If a brain-reading device is available, integrate it with the glove to provide additional control options to the drone.

Constraints:

* Budget: The total project budget is $400, which must cover sensor purchase, microchips, materials for building the glove, and any other required hardware  
* Timeframe: The project must be completed within one semester, so the design and testing phases need to be efficient.

## 1.3 Solution Summary {#1.3-solution-summary}

The solution involves developing a wearable device, a glove or hat of sorts that will detect inputs from sensors to control a drone. The glove will be designed to detect hand and arm movements, while the brain-computer interface (BCI) will capture neural signals that can be used to control the drone. The system will be adaptive, allowing users with various levels of dexterity to control the drone based on their unique abilities. The key innovation is combining physical gesture control with the potential of BCIs, enabling an inclusive experience for users of varying mobility levels.

## 1.4 Evaluation Summary {#1.4-evaluation-summary}

Functional Evaluation:

* Latency Testing: The time it takes after a user moves for the drone to respond.  
* Sensor Functionality: How accurate the sensors are. Sensors will be tested for consistency across different movements.  
* Sensitivity Adjustments: The system will be tested to determine how well it can adapt to the users needs.

Behavioral Evaluation:

* Ease of Use: Users will be asked to control the drone using the interface. Their ability to control the drone effectively and intuitively will be a key evaluation criteria.  
* Adaptability: Will the system be able to adjust to different levels of usability but maintain similar control.  
* User Feedback: Users will provide feedback on their experience highlighting any difficulties in control or comfort.

# 3 Requirements {#3-requirements}

The brain-reader project aims to develop a low cost device that can amplify and process low-noise neural signals, integrate with a microprocessor that can run the data through a neural network to output signals to control a drone. The following subsections outline the key requirements, user stories and success criteria.

Functional Requirements:

1) Signal Amplification: The device must amplify weak brain waves while maintaining low noise.  
2) Noise Filtering: The system should implement filtering techniques to reduce unwanted noise.  
3) Real-time Processing: Ensure real-time processing of brainwave signals to enable near instant control responses.  
4) Wireless Communication: Allows data transmission from microcontroller to other devices.  
5) User Interface: Provide a simple UI for calibration and monitoring.  
6) Data Logging: Support data logging for analysis and improvements.  
   

Non-Functional Requirements:

1) Reliability: The system must be consistent.  
2) Scalability: The design should leave room for improvement, like room for adding more nodes.  
3) Power Efficiency: The device should optimize battery life for prolonged use.  
4) Compliance: Adhere to relevant medical and electronic safety standards.

## 3.2 Definition of Success {#3.2-definition-of-success}

Success will be determined by the following criteria:

1) Signal Accuracy: If someone is thinking one thing we want the system to also realize that.  
2) Low Noise Processing: Signal to noise ratio improves by at least 20dB  
3) Real-time Performance: Processing latency remains below 50ms  
4) Hardware Integration: All sensors and parts interface with the microprocessor and wireless communication module.  
5) User Experience: Most of the users are comfortable.  
6) Data Logging Efficiency: Logs signals with low loss  
7) Power Efficiency: Operates for a designated period of time  
8) Safety Compliance: Passes relevant safety and regulatory tests  
9) Scalability: Final product leaves room for improvement.

# 5 Design Exploration {#5-design-exploration}

This project focuses on developing a drone that is controlled purely through EEG signals, which would maximize the accessibility for individuals with disabilities. The goal is to eliminate traditional hand-controlled methods to ensure a hands-free experience. 

## 5.1 Comparison of Potential Solutions {#5.1-comparison-of-potential-solutions}

Below listed are potential solutions

1. A drone controlled by brainwaves and facial expressions, using EEG to track brain activity. It will also see what the face of the user is doing and react accordingly. \[1\]  
2. A drone that follows a predetermined path, set by the user and specifically supposed to focus on the viewer with a camera. \[2\]  
3. A drone with multiple types of automated paths to follow, one of which is just to follow and focus on the user. \[3\]

While these solutions are all creative and are tangential to what we are attempting to do, which is maximize accessibility with drone control, we are specifically focusing on EEG signals to control the drone. No predetermined flight pattern or reading of any facial signals, like some listed above, rather purely brain signals

Reference:

## 5.3 Pilot Studies {#5.3-pilot-studies}

For our pilot studies we began by showing our lo-fi diagram of our system, describing how our system would work, as illustrated in the system design, with the helmet scanning for specific brain waves, sending in data to both our database and also an ML algorithm focusing the data for the drone, which would be sent to fully compute along with the database data to control the drone, then finally leading to a feedback loop where the drone feedback will be sent to the system and vice versa to ensure maximum stability. Then we showed the way the helmet would actually work, with specific nodes placed on specific parts of the head to capture the correct data. Finally, we showed the website that sends data from the drone, including charge, latency, camera feed, and more. There is also specific brain data shown, illustrating what is being tracked. Finally if there is some error there is a way to control the drone from this site.

## 5.4 Inclusion, Diversity, Equity, and Accessibility Considerations {#5.4-inclusion,-diversity,-equity,-and-accessibility-considerations}

The need for robotics in an industry where disabled people are present is increasing every year. “In 2023, 22.5 percent of people with a disability were employed—the highest recorded ratio since comparable data were first collected in 2008…The unemployment rate for people with a disability (7.2 percent) was little changed in 2023, while the rate for those without a disability was unchanged over the year at 3.5 percent.” \[1\] The present issue at hand is increasing participation of disabled people within the workforce, where gains are already being made since 2023\. “During the labor market recovery following the COVID-19 pandemic, disabled people have made notable employment gains, benefiting from opportunities created by tight labor market conditions and increased workplace flexibilities” \[2\] 

The workplace becoming more flexible is opening the market again to people who have been ostracized compared to their able-bodied peers. However, there is still progress to be made. Workers who are or become disabled can experience societal pressures due to the disability. “\[Disabilities\] may be a more peripheral attribute that influences established role identities, such as when a worker acquires an impairment after he or she already has established a strong work identity. An example case study showed that workers with severe impairments might deny their disability identities in a work environment when the organization places a strong emphasis on the talent levels of employees” \[3\].It is therefore in the best interest of employers to retain workers who are talented, but struggle from impairments. 

To this end, it is our belief that a drone that is controlled by your brain would accomplish the goal of increasing workforce participation, without experiencing any setbacks that currently affect disabled people. We can expect the brain-controlled drone to become a vital component in construction and maintenance for performing tasks that are too dangerous or too cumbersome for workers. The drone would have the ability to reach areas that are otherwise inaccessible due to extenuating circumstances, therefore increasing the safety of workers and increasing productivity at workplaces.

# 6 System Design {#6-system-design}

## 6.1 Functional Design {#6.1-functional-design}

![][image5]

The Figure above shows a basic system design of our proposed system with 8 nodes. Where each node has its own preamp. Each pair of nodes will connect to a set of differential amplifiers which will then be filtered through a band pass filter. Lastly, the data will be sent through an arduino nano to process into digital information to then be sent to a raspberry pi where the data will be sent through a neural network. We will be using a database made in Postgres to store all of the data from users to the brainwaves that are caused by certain thoughts. The Rasp Pi will download the data of one user and send that data through a neural network that will then be able to do real time computations of the current brainwaves of the user so that they can control something.

![][image6]

The figure above shows a more part level design of one slice of the total system. These are the layouts of the preamp, differential amp and band pass filter that we plan on using.

![][image7]

This is the preamp that we will be using. You will have the node data go into S- and the amplified data come out of Vout.

![][image8]

The differential amplifier will take the amplified signal from the preamp and compare two nodes data that will be sent forward.

![][image9]

The band pass filter will filter the data so that only 8Hz \- 200Hz goes to the Arduino Nano.

## 6.2 Data Design {#6.2-data-design}

![][image10]

Input user and EEG data is collected, processed, and stored.  Wave data is stored in a database, with its wave type, frequency, amplitude, and power attributes. This data is then linked to the associated training model. Each training model and the wave input and associated command is stored in a database to serve as a control log. Users are saved in the database and are linked to an associated training model. 

![][image11]

This figure shows the entity relationship between the stored Wave, Training Model, User, and Command tables. Wave data is put into the wave table and is linked to the training model table. The command associated with the training model based on the wave data is also associated with the training model. Finally the user table is linked to the training model, as each user may or may not have a stored training\_model associated with them.

# Appendix A: Project Management {#appendix-a:-project-management}

## A.1 Team Agreement {#a.1-team-agreement}

# Team Goals and Objectives

* Research and buy all Dry EEG sensors (Ag based), Preamps (AD620)  
  1) The  Dry sensors are needed as wet sensors are expensive and uncomfortable to wear for long periods of time. Also the agent that completes contact between the node and the skin will dry over time and cause increased impedance.  
  2) Preamps will magnify the initial 10-100 microvolt signal from the sensors to the filters. Creating a stronger signal will reduce the effect of noise distortion providing more accurate readings. This will also allow us to differentiate the noise in the nano to pi signal from the actual data from the node.  
* Test and get an understanding of all necessary sensors  
* Plug sensors into micro-chip Arduino Nano 33 iot and test the outputs on a closed system  
* Implement an EEG recording system, with  90% measurement comparability to an established medical grade system.  
* Data filtering system to isolate different brainwave readings in the range of 8 to 59 Hz.  
* Data storage system to hold user trials measurements.  
* Send commands to drone from device (not based on sensor inputs)  
* Create a system that will teach the user how to use the device while also gathering data that is necessary for the machine learning model.  
* Send commands to drone from device based on sensor inputs  
* Create a more efficient training set for users to optimize the BCI.  
* Design an enjoyable course that encourages users to fully complete it, so they can fully utilize the control system.  
* Have user machine learning models have 90% accuracy between user intent and control signal output.
